&gt; way, to some degree they have overcome some of that shyness in 
order to post whatever it 
&gt; was to begin with, which inspired him to make this offer. What if 
they don&#39;t even have the 
&gt; gumption to be anything more than be a look-i-loo?
&gt; 
&gt; I&#39;m guessing many people are just surfing the net, checking out 
paranormal stuff, and run 
&gt; across the hacked boxes for sale. 
&gt; 
&gt; Again, I ask people who are taking the position you and Bruce are 
regarding profits ... do 
&gt; you have this same harsh sentiment toward Ron Ricketts, who makes 
and sells the 
&gt; MiniBoxes? I realize he is passionate about this research and 
helping others. Does that 
&gt; give him amnesty for making a profit? 
&gt; 
&gt; Personally I think we need to not be so judgmental. At what point 
does &quot;profitable gain in 
&gt; the paranormal field&quot; become &quot;sickening?&quot; I have a friend who is a 
medium. I mean THE 
&gt; REAL DEAL. He charges for his services. The fee is reasonable 
compared to many in his 
&gt; field. Does he do this because he&#39;s a terrible person looking to 
take advantage of people? 
&gt; NO, he does so because he has been given a gift that changes 
people&#39;s lives for the better. 
&gt; But he has to make a living.... has to support himself in some way. 
And because he has 
&gt; chosen to provide this service full time (and is not a trust fund 
baby), he makes a profit. 
&gt; This allows him to help far more people than he could if working 
some other kind of job 
&gt; and providing his services at no cost on the side. 
&gt; 
&gt; I realize this is not exactly the same thing as gouging people on 
the price for a 
&gt; commercially available product, but making such blanket statements 
about profitability in 
&gt; the paranormal field being sickening is rather short-sighted, in my 
opinion. 
&gt; 
&gt; I have a southern friend who likes to say, &quot;It&#39;s a mighty thin 
plank that ain&#39;t got two sides.&quot; 
&gt; I just don&#39;t think we have the right to claim that simply because 
someone is offering a 
&gt; good and or service for profit to consumers in the paranormal 
market, that this 
&gt; automatically means they are taking advantage of other&#39;s 
vulnerabilities. 
&gt; 
&gt; For Pete&#39;s sake, no one is twisting the people&#39;s arms to buy those 
units on eBay. They are 
&gt; perfectly free to buy from whatever source they choose. Since the 
units do work as 
&gt; claimed, we can argue that people have overpaid, shopped unwisely, 
or whatever. I assure 
&gt; you this happens every single day throughout the retail market 
place with all types of 
&gt; products and services. 
&gt; 
&gt; I will say I have a fairly heathy dose of distain for 
charlatans/scam artists (of any flavor in 
&gt; any field) but that is not what we are talking about here. We are 
talking about people who 
&gt; are offering legitimate products to consumers. I&#39;d rather see 
people doing this for profit, 
&gt; even when obscene, than running scams that damage people&#39;s 
physical, mental, and/or 
&gt; financial well-being. 
&gt; 
&gt; Margaret
&gt; 
&gt; --- In EVP-ITC@yahoogroups .com, Early Cuyler &lt;ecuyler@ &gt; wrote:
